'''Fudoki of Owari Province''' (尾張国風土記) was the [[Fudoki]] of {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国}}, compiled during the [[Nara period]]. The full text does not survive, and only a few fragments ({{ill|fragments|ja|逸文}}) are preserved through later sources.
== Overview == The ''Fudoki of Owari Province'' was compiled in the early [[8th century]]. Like other extant Fudoki, it likely recorded local place names and traditions. However, much of the text was lost by the Edo period. The fragments now available are citations in later works such as {{ill|Shaku Nihongi|ja|釈日本紀}}, {{ill|Chinbukuro|ja|塵袋}}, and {{ill|Man'yōshū Commentary|ja|万葉集註釈}}{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|pp=47-58}}.
A work titled ''Owari Fudoki'' is held by the {{ill|Aichi Prefectural Library|ja|愛知県立図書館}}, but it is part of the early modern forgery ''Nihon Sōkoku Fudoki'' and unrelated to the original ancient compilation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://websv.aichi-pref-library.jp/wahon/detail/95.html|title=【地誌】尾張国風土記|accessdate=2024-12-01|publisher=Aichi Prefectural Library}}</ref>.
== Contents == The surviving fragments attributed to the ''Fudoki of Owari Province'' are summarized below{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|pp=47-58}}.
=== Atsuta Shrine === {{Quotation| Atsuta Shrine: In ancient times, during the return of {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武命}} from his journey to the eastern provinces, he married {{ill|Miyasuhime|ja|宮簀媛}}, an ancestor of the {{ill|Owari clan|ja|尾張連}}. Staying at her home, Yamato Takeru hung his sword on a mulberry tree near the restroom. When he went to retrieve it, the sword glowed with divine radiance, leading him to declare it sacred. He instructed Miyasuhime to enshrine the sword as his own shadow and reflection, thus establishing Atsuta Shrine.{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=47}} |''Shaku Nihongi,'' Volume 7}}
This fragment is cited in ''Shaku Nihongi'' and describes the origins of {{ill|Atsuta Shrine|ja|熱田神宮}}, detailing the enshrinement of the {{ill|Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi|ja|草薙剣}}. It parallels accounts in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'' and ''{{ill|Owari no Kuni Atsuta Daijingū Engi|ja|尾張国熱田太神宮縁起}}''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archives.bukkyo-u.ac.jp/rp-contents/DB/0049/DB00490R027.pdf|title=『尾張国熱田太神宮縁起』を読む-『古語拾遺』との比較から-|accessdate=2024-12-01|author=Taniguchi Jun|editor=Bukkyo University Graduate School of Literature|format=PDF}}</ref>.
=== Miyake Temple === {{Quotation| Owari Province, Aichi District, Fukuyuki Temple{{Efn|Also called Fukuyoshi Temple.}} (commonly known as Miyake Temple), located 9 ''ri'' and 14 steps south of the district seat in the Hinokuma Village of Nikabe Township. During the reign of Emperor Shōmu, in the first year of Jingkei (724), the temple was built by Miyake no Muraji Masa, a senior official (''Jushichi-i''){{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=51}}. |''Man'yōshū Commentary,'' Volume 1}}
This fragment describes Fukuyuki Temple, also known as Miyake Temple, in Aichi District. It states that the temple was established in 724 by a local official, Miyake no Muraji Masa{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=51}}.
=== Azura Township === {{Quotation| During the reign of Emperor Suinin at the Makimuku no Mizugaki Palace, Prince Homutsuwake reached the age of seven but had not yet spoken. The Empress dreamed of a god identifying itself as Amanomikatsuhime, demanding worship. The god claimed that by assigning someone to serve them, the prince would gain speech and long life. The Emperor ordered a divination, and Takao no Kimi was sent to locate the deity. He made a garland (''kazura'') from sacred tree branches, saying, "Where this garland falls, the god must reside." It fell in this place, and a shrine was built. The name Azura comes from this origin.{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=51}} |''Shaku Nihongi,'' Volume 10}}
This passage explains the etymology of "Azura Township" in {{ill|Niwa District|ja|丹羽郡}}, linked to the founding of the {{ill|Azura Shrine|ja|阿豆良神社}}.
=== Kawashima Shrine === {{Quotation| Kawashima Shrine: Located in Kawashima Village of Kawanuma Township, Hakuri District. During the reign of Emperor Shōmu, it was reported by Omikumi no Oshihito that the deity appeared as a white deer. The Emperor issued a decree to enshrine the deity as a heavenly shrine.{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=50}} |''Man'yōshū Commentary,'' Volume 1}}
This fragment concerns {{ill|Kawashima Shrine (Kōnan City)|ja|川島神社}} in Hakuri District. It recounts the shrine's establishment during the reign of Emperor Shōmu after a divine manifestation{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=50}}.
