'''Owari no Kuni Fudoki''' (尾張国風土記) was the [[Fudoki]] of [[:en:Owari Province|Owari Province]], compiled during the [[Nara period]]. The full text does not survive, and only a few fragments ([[:en:Lost literary work|fragments]]) are preserved through later sources.
== Overview == The ''Fudoki of Owari Province'' was compiled in the early [[8th century]]. Like other extant Fudoki, it likely recorded local place names and traditions. However, much of the text was lost by the Edo period. The fragments now available are citations in later works such as [[:en:Shaku Nihongi|Shaku Nihongi]], {{ill|Chinbukuro|ja|塵袋|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinbukuro|qq=}}, and {{ill|Man'yōshū Commentary|ja|万葉集註釈|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Man'yōshū Commentary|qq=}}{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|pp=47-58}}.
A work titled ''Owari Fudoki'' is held by the {{ill|Aichi Prefectural Library|ja|愛知県立図書館|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aichi Prefectural Library|qq=}}, but it is part of the early modern forgery ''Nihon Sōkoku Fudoki'' and unrelated to the original ancient compilation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://websv.aichi-pref-library.jp/wahon/detail/95.html|title=【地誌】尾張国風土記|accessdate=2024-12-01|publisher=Aichi Prefectural Library}}</ref>.
== Contents == The surviving fragments attributed to the ''Fudoki of Owari Province'' are summarized below{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|pp=47-58}}.
=== Atsuta Shrine === {{Quotation| Atsuta Shrine: In ancient times, during the return of {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武命|1=Yamato Takeru|2=ja|3=ヤマトタケル|4=fr|5=Yamato Takeru|6=zh|7=日本武尊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Takeru|qq=}} from his journey to the eastern provinces, he married [[:en:Miyazu-hime|Miyasuhime]], an ancestor of the {{ill|Owari clan|ja|尾張連|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari clan|qq=}}. Staying at her home, Yamato Takeru hung his sword on a mulberry tree near the restroom. When he went to retrieve it, the sword glowed with divine radiance, leading him to declare it sacred. He instructed Miyasuhime to enshrine the sword as his own shadow and reflection, thus establishing Atsuta Shrine.{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=47}} |''Shaku Nihongi,'' Volume 7}}
This fragment is cited in ''Shaku Nihongi'' and describes the origins of [[:en:Atsuta Shrine|Atsuta Shrine]], detailing the enshrinement of the {{ill|Kusanagi no Tsurugi|lt=Kusanagi no Tsurugi|lt=Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi|ja|草薙剣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi|qq=}}. It parallels accounts in the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'' and ''{{ill|Owari no Kuni Atsuta Daijingū Engi|ja|尾張国熱田太神宮縁起|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari no Kuni Atsuta Daijingū Engi|qq=}}''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archives.bukkyo-u.ac.jp/rp-contents/DB/0049/DB00490R027.pdf|title=『尾張国熱田太神宮縁起』を読む-『古語拾遺』との比較から-|accessdate=2024-12-01|author=Taniguchi Jun|editor=Bukkyo University Graduate School of Literature|format=PDF}}</ref>.
=== Miyake Temple === {{Quotation| Owari Province, Aichi District, Fukuyuki Temple{{Efn|Also called Fukuyoshi Temple.}} (commonly known as Miyake Temple), located 9 ''ri'' and 14 steps south of the district seat in the Hinokuma Village of Nikabe Township. During the reign of Emperor Shōmu, in the first year of Jingkei (724), the temple was built by Miyake no Muraji Masa, a senior official (''Jushichi-i''){{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=51}}. |''Man'yōshū Commentary,'' Volume 1}}
This fragment describes Fukuyuki Temple, also known as Miyake Temple, in Aichi District. It states that the temple was established in 724 by a local official, Miyake no Muraji Masa{{Sfn|Kurita Kan|1927|p=51}}.
